Rating: 0
1 ounce dried porcini mushrooms 2 cups boiling water 6oz fresh baby bella mushrooms, chopped fine 2 tablespoons unsalted butter 2 to 3 cups low-salt chicken broth 4 ounces diced pancetta 11/2 cup finely chopped onion 1 tablespoon finely chopped fresh rosemary leaves 1 tablespoon finely chopped fresh sage leaves 1 cup Arborio rice 1/2-3/4 cup Parmesan cheese In a small bowl soak porcini in boiling water 30 minutes. Pour soaking liquid through a fine sieve lined with a dampened paper towel or coffee filter into a bowl and reserve. Pat dry mushrooms. Chop porcini fine. In a large saucepan heat broth and keep at a bare simmer. In a 5-to-6 quart heavy saucepan cook pancetta over moderate heat, stirring, 5 minutes. One at a time, add onion, 1/2 baby bella mushrooms, butter, rosemary, sage, and salt and pepper to taste; stirring, until onion is softened. Stir in rice and cook, stirring, until coated well with fat, about 1 minute. Add 1 cup broth and cook, stirring constantly, until absorbed. Continue cooking and adding broth, 1/4 cup at a time, stirring constantly and letting each addition be absorbed before adding next, After 2 cups of broth, add 1/2 baby bella mushrooms, And switch to reserved porcini water, still 1/4 cup at a time. Halfway into the reserved porcini water, add the porcini mushrooms continue until rice is tender and creamy-looking but still al dente, 20 to 25 minutes. stir grated Parmesan and salt and pepper to taste.

Rating: 3
Not quick but simple and delicious. Works well with other ingedients if you don't have the right mushrooms for example.

Rating: 3
After teasing my husband that he would be a full fledged cook if he could make me a risotto, he made this recipe for me. It was very good. The only change we made was to use half pancetta, half bacon. I liked the periodic taste of the bacon in it. The meal was quite a bit of work, even for a risotto. It's definitely one where you should start with an empty dishwasher and have someone cleaning as you cook. I also would turn this into 7 or 8 servings in the future, especially if serving anything else with it. It does reheat okay, but consider adding just a touch of water or broth while reheating it.

